(4) Moreover, nearly every adjective and adverb in the language is intensified by the prefix per- 1 and miti- gated by the prefix m. This is to be expected, owing to the need arising in letters for conveying delicate shades of meaning. This need demands also that minute gradua- tion of the force of a word which the use of the compara- tive and superlative can so well supply in Latin. Hence the extraordinary richness of the letters in comparative and superlative forms both in adjectives and adverbs‚ for which see Stinner, pp. 12-15.
